Description: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. The rear shows one side with a larger row of basketry coil and a second side with two smaller rows of basketry coil suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side is flat and shows a complete impression of an oval scarab-like seal is visible. Many finger impressions are visible around the seal impression. Recognisable is a lying ram, facing towards the left, wearing a double feather crown with uraei. In front of the ram a seated figure, probably MAa.t, facing towards the left. Above the back of the ram an uraeus with wings in protection gesture, facing towards the left.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
